In this speech delivered at the Eisenhower Executive Office Building, Second Gentleman Douglas Emhoff expresses gratitude to the audience for their work in addressing the opioid crisis. He emphasizes the importance of eliminating the stigma associated with overdoses and investing in mental health resources. Emhoff acknowledges the impact of the crisis on individuals from all walks of life and highlights the administration's commitment to addressing the issue. He mentions the administration's investment in the National Drug Control strategy and the positive results achieved in flattening overdose rates. Emhoff announces an additional $450 million investment to support prevention, harm reduction, treatment, and recovery services in local communities. He praises the audience for their leadership and calls for continued collaboration to build safer and healthier communities. The speech concludes with a transition to Dr. Mandy Cohen, the Director for the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.